  failures: {
    eyebrow: "Common failure patterns",
    title: "Redaction fails when the surrounding data flow remains invisible.",
    introduction:
      "Automated masking can create a strong visual signal of safety while originals, mappings, contextual identifiers, logs, and downstream inferences remain available elsewhere.",
    items: [
      {
        title: "Pattern matching becomes the privacy program",
        description:
          "Regular expressions catch familiar formats but miss contextual identity, uncommon formats, linked attributes, sensitive meaning, and data represented across several fields.",
      },
      {
        title: "The token is protected but the mapping is not",
        description:
          "Transformed values appear anonymous while a broadly accessible lookup table, shared key, or stable identifier makes re-identification straightforward.",
      },
      {
        title: "Useful context is removed without testing",
        description:
          "Aggressive scrubbing changes the meaning needed for service, fairness, fraud, accessibility, safety, or quality, creating a new operating risk.",
      },
      {
        title: "Logs preserve what the prompt removed",
        description:
          "The application sanitizes model input after raw content has already entered observability, analytics, error tracking, support tooling, or temporary storage.",
      },
      {
        title: "Exceptions become permanent bypasses",
        description:
          "A legitimate edge case receives an override, but scope, duration, owner, review, and removal are not recorded, allowing sensitive data to flow indefinitely.",
      },
      {
        title: "A vendor setting is treated as end-to-end proof",
        description:
          "Provider retention or training controls are reviewed while upstream collection, application logs, integrations, human access, and downstream outputs remain unexamined.",
      },
